Marine shrimps of the genus
Farfantepenaeus Burukovsky, 1997
are one of the most exploited fishing resources along the Brazilian coast due to their high market value (
;
). Despite this commercial importance, all species belonging to this genus are commonly known as “camarões-rosa” (= pink shrimps) along the Brazilian coast (
;
). However, the exploitation rate of each species is variable along the coast due to their different latitudinal distributions.For example,
Farfantepenaeus subtilis (Pérez-Farfante, 1967)
can be found from the Caribbean Sea ( 20°N ) to Cabo Frio ( Rio de Janeiro , southeastern Brazil , 23°S ), whereas
Farfantepenaeus paulensis (Pérez-Farfante, 1967)
occurs from Ilhéus ( Bahia , northeastern Brazil , 14°S ) to Mar del Plata ( Argentina , 38°S ) (
;
). On the other hand,
Farfantepenaeus brasiliensis (Latreille, 1817)
shows a wider distribution than the two previously mentioned species, occurring from North Carolina (USA, 35°N ) to Rio Grande do Sul (southern Brazil , 33°S ) (
;
)
.

The total catch of
Farfantepenaeus spp.
in Brazil was about 10.3 thousand tonnes in 2011, the last year for which catch statistics were available at a national level (
). This amount was surpassed only by the Atlantic seabob shrimp,
Xiphopenaeus kroyeri (Heller, 1862)
, with total catches of 15.4 thousand tonnes (
). The total catch of
Farfantepenaeus spp.
on the coast of Sergipe ( 11°S ) was about 176.6 tonnes in 2014 (
). However, it should be noted that in both national and local reports, there was no discrimination of catch by species, making it difficult to assess the exploitation status of each stock (
;
;
)
.

Farfantepenaeus brasiliensis
can be found from shallow water to 366 m of depth, inhabiting detritusrich muddy to gravel-sandy bottoms, and reach a size at first maturity at about 150 mm of total length (
). This species has a type II life cycle, in which reproduction and egg release take place offshore and the post-larvae migrate to estuarine areas where they grow up to juvenile/subadult stages and then move back offshore to complete their life cycles (
). Therefore,
F.brasiliensis
fishery may target two population groups: juveniles/subadults in estuaries and inshore habitats and/or adults offshore (
).

Several population studies have estimated biometric relationships for penaeids and these relationships have been highlighted as an important tool for assessing the status of shrimp stocks, as very often different morphological traits may ref lect environmental inf luences or overfishing impacts (

; Dumond and D’Incao, 2010; 

; 

, 

; 

). Biometric relationships for 

F.brasiliensis

have already been estimated for southern and southeastern 
Brazil
(

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

) as well as for the Gulf of Mexico (

; 

; 

). Nevertheless, there is no information about this species for northeastern 
Brazil
. Here, 

F. brasiliensis

from the coast of the 
Sergipe
was studied to understand the biometric relationships and sex ratio of this species. Additionally, data from the present study were compared with those obtained from other populations to assess the variation of the traits studied along its distribution range.

A chi-square test (Χ²) with the Yates correction (

) was applied to test if the sex ratio differed statistically from 1:1. The mean length and wet weight of females and males were compared using t-tests with different variances (

). The relationships TL 
vs
CL, TL 
vs
RL and RL 
vs
CL were fitted using linear equations (Y=a+bX), while a power equation was fitted to both WW 
vs
TL and W W 
vs
CL relationships (Y=a∙ 
Xb
; 

). All relationships were estimated for females and males, separately, and then compared using an analysis of covariance (

). The hypothesis of isometry was tested for the length-length relationships (b=1) and weight-length relationships (b=3) using t-tests (

; 

). All statistical tests were performed with a significance level of 5%.

All individuals of
F. brasiliensis
smaller than 25 mm CL are considered juveniles in southeastern Brazil (
;
). In this study, 28 specimens (22% of total) caught were lower than 25 mm CL, however only one female individual was immature. In this way, our data corresponds to an adult population, which is exploited by the shrimp fleet along the coast of Sergipe
.

The largest specimens observed on the coast of Sergipe ( 11°S ) (189.18 and 145.90 mm TL for females and males, respectively) were smaller than those recorded in southeastern Brazil ( 23°S ).
recorded maximum sizes of 210 and 180 mm TL for females and males, respectively, while
found values of 260 and 219 mm TL (both studies in coastal waters off the state of São Paulo ). Larger values (266 and 219mm TL for females and males, respectively) were also recorded off Mexico ( 21°N ) (
). All three studies also analyzed data from shrimp fisheries landings. These variations in body size can be influenced by habitat conditions ( e.g. , water temperature and food/ nutrient supply) correlated with latitude (
), where an increase in body size is commonly observed with increasing latitude (
), in this case in both hemispheres
.

The sex ratio of 1:1observed here is very common in penaeids (

), especially for populations occupying relatively constant environments (

). Likewise, sexual dimorphism is a very common trait in penaeids, with females being larger than males, which has also been observed for 

F. brasiliensis

in our study, and also by 

, 

, 

, 

, 

, and 

. This dimorphism ref lects a reproductive strategy, as larger size for females allows for larger gonads and higher fertility and, thus, maximizes egg production (

). As most organs of shrimps, including the reproductive ones, are located in the carapace, differences between sexes in the TL/CL ratio are expected, with females having a proportionally larger carapace than males as an adaptation to maximize egg production. Indeed, these differences in the TL/CL ratio are not observed when analyzing juveniles (

).

Morphometric relationships vary according to the length/age, with younger, smaller individuals having higher slopes than older, larger individuals requiring different equations for conversions (

; 

; 

). Most of the morphometric data available for 

F. brasiliensis

are from juveniles/subadults inhabiting coastal habitats such as estuaries and coastal lagoons (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

), which differ from the equations for adults such as the ones obtained here in the coast of 
Sergipe
.

All length-length relationships estimated here, except for RL vs CL, showed positive allometry corroborating previous records for this shrimp species in southeastern-southern Brazil (
;
). The same pattern has also been reported for other penaeids (
;
;
;
) suggesting that positive allometry for TL vs CL relationship is a common trait for these shrimps. Regarding the RL vs CL relationship,
also reported a negative allometry for juveniles of
F. brasiliensis
off Mexico . However, studies carried out with
X. kroyeri
indicated differences in the RL vs CL relationship between juveniles and adults, with faster increase (positive allometry) being observed in juveniles (
). Faster increase of the rostrum length during the juvenile stage could be a strategy of this species to avoid predation, as observed in
X. kroyeri (
Moraes et al. , 2018
)

The weight-length relationships showed contrasting patterns. When the W W 
vs
TL relationship was estimated, the allometry was positive for both sexes indicating a higher increase in weight than expected by the increase in total length. 

recorded a positive allometry for adult males and negative for adult females caught along the southeastern Brazilian coast. Later, an inverse pattern was recorded for the same region (

; 

). According to 

, the positive allometric growth presented by females is associated with the gain in weight due to gonad development. For the Mexican coast, this relationship was negative for both sexes (

). When the W W 
vs
CL relationship was estimated, the allometry was negative.

